  "opinion": "As a woman in my sixties who's spent decades building things with my hands—both wood and relationships—I've learned that the most honest way to deal with fake content online is to slow down and question before you share. My days on social media are long, but I've found that taking a moment to check the source, like I would before cutting a piece of wood, helps me avoid spreading misinformation. I remember when my husband and I first started gardening together, we always checked the soil before planting to make sure it was the right type. That same care applies to the content we see. I've noticed that many fake posts come from people who are trying to manipulate emotions, much like a poorly constructed frame that doesn't hold up under pressure. With my high neuroticism, I get anxious when things feel off, so I've learned to use that sensitivity as a tool—when something feels 'too good to be true,' I pause and ask myself: 'Is this really helpful, or is it just trying to distract me?' My creativity helps me visualize the consequences of sharing false information, and my low extraversion means I don't need to be loud about it; a simple, thoughtful message can do the job. I've also started to share my own experiences with my children, teaching them to verify before they post, just as we teach them to check their tools before using them. It's about being patient and deliberate, not rushing to judgment, and that's something I've learned from both my hands and my heart.",
